    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/899032290/lesson-22-рд╣-рди-to-be" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="Today we&rsquo;re going to cover probably the most common Hindi word - so that means we should all pay our best attention yeah? Well here goes! The word we&rsquo;re going to be learning is&nbsp;-&nbsp;&#2361;&#2379;&#2344;&#2366; honaa - it means &lsquo;to be&rsquo;. In an actual sentence it usually translates to &ldquo;am&rdquo;, &ldquo;is&rdquo; or &ldquo;are&rdquo; and we&rsquo;ll see this in a minute so hold tight.&nbsp;


 Now I want you to step back from Hindi and think about English a second. If I said &ldquo;I is&rdquo; or &ldquo;you am&rdquo; you&rsquo;d look at me and tell me I&rsquo;m wrong, because that&rsquo;s not how the sentence should be. Well exactly the same concept applies for Hindi!&nbsp;









 It&rsquo;s so important to have correct grammar when talking - otherwise, like this cat, no one&rsquo;s going to be able to understand you!&nbsp;






 So first let&rsquo;s learn how&nbsp;&#2361;&#2379;&#2344;&#2366; honaa changes and then we&rsquo;ll see a bunch examples - does that sound like a good idea? Here we&rsquo;ll use what we learnt from&nbsp;Lesson #15 Pronouns, if you can&rsquo;t remember that lesson then go back to it and revise over it!&nbsp;So are you ready to get going? Deep breath!&nbsp;


 &#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;main hoon &nbsp;- &nbsp;I am


 &#2361;&#2350; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;ham hain &nbsp; - &nbsp; We&nbsp;are


 &#2340;&#2370; &#2361;&#2376;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;too hai &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp; You are (Intimate)


 &#2310;&#2346; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;aap hain &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp; You are (Formal)


 &#2340;&#2369;&#2350; &#2361;&#2379;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;tum ho &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; You are (Casual)


 (Remember we learnt in&nbsp;Lesson #15 Pronouns&nbsp;that Hindi has three different word for 'you&rsquo; - so if you can&rsquo;t remember their difference head back to that lesson!)


 &#2351;&#2361; &#2361;&#2376; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;yeh hai &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;He / She / This is &nbsp;(Near)


 &#2351;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ye hain &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;These / They are &nbsp;(Near)


 &#2357;&#2361; &#2361;&#2376; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;voh hai &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;He / She / That is (Far)


 &#2357;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ve hain &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;Those / They are (Far)&nbsp;


 Phew! How was there? There&rsquo;s a lot to remember don&rsquo;t you think? Well actually there&rsquo;s just three (and a bit) rules you really need to know -&nbsp;


 
 &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; hoon means 'am&rsquo;. So whenever you want to say 'I am&rsquo; you&rsquo;ll say &#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; main hoon.


 &#2361;&#2376;&nbsp;hai means 'is&rsquo;. So whenever you want to say 'is&rsquo; you&rsquo;ll say &#2361;&#2376;&nbsp;hai


 &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;&nbsp;hain means 'are&rsquo;. So whenever you want to say 'are&rsquo; you&rsquo;ll say &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;&nbsp;hain.



 There&rsquo;s two exceptions to this though; We use &#2361;&#2379; ho for &#2340;&#2369;&#2350; tum and we use&nbsp;&#2361;&#2376; hai for &#2340;&#2370; too. It can be tricky to remember I know so keep practicing and you&rsquo;ll get there! &nbsp;


 Now do you think you&rsquo;re ready for a few examples? Before we start there&rsquo;s one thing you need to know - in Hindi the always verb comes at the end of the sentence! This means we literally say &ldquo;I Nita am&rdquo; or &ldquo;this house is&rdquo;. This can be super confusing to new learners so be sure to go through the examples slowly!





&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2344;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; main neetaa hoon&nbsp;- I am Nita&nbsp;


 Can you see what&rsquo;s happened here? If you don&rsquo;t know, &#2344;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366; nitaa is a common girls name in india. Remember we are literally saying &ldquo;I Nita am&rdquo;. Ready for another example?





&#2357;&#2375; &#2325;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366;&#2348;&#2375;&#2306; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;&nbsp;ve kitaaben hain&nbsp;- They are books





 &#2351;&#2361; &#2348;&#2367;&#2354;&#2381;&#2354;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376;&nbsp;yeh billee hai&nbsp;- This is [a/the] cat





&#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;? aap kaise hain? - How are you?


 We&rsquo;ve learnt this phrase, &ldquo;how are you?&rdquo;, and how to reply to it, already in&nbsp;Lesson #17&nbsp;- so feel free to check it out!&nbsp;


 Phew ok! How&rsquo;s that? Can you follow the examples? There might be some words you don&rsquo;t understand in the sentences but don&rsquo;t worry, just make sure you can spot the&nbsp;&#2361;&#2379;&#2344;&#2366;&nbsp;honaa&nbsp;and how and why it&rsquo;s changed in each sentence! Try writing your own sentences and leave them as a comment below for practice!&nbsp;


