        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-22-to-be">Lesson #22: рд╣реЛрдирд╛ - To Be</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Today we&rsquo;re going to cover probably the most common Hindi word - so that means we should all pay our best attention yeah? Well here goes! The word we&rsquo;re going to be learning is&nbsp;-&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2379;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>honaa </em>- it means &lsquo;to be&rsquo;. In an actual sentence it usually translates to &ldquo;am&rdquo;, &ldquo;is&rdquo; or &ldquo;are&rdquo; and we&rsquo;ll see this in a minute so hold tight.&nbsp;</p><p>Now I want you to step back from Hindi and think about English a second. If I said &ldquo;I is&rdquo; or &ldquo;you am&rdquo; you&rsquo;d look at me and tell me I&rsquo;m wrong, because that&rsquo;s not how the sentence should be. Well exactly the same concept applies for Hindi!&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mdot8k8uxb1qzfx8l.png"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mdotgwi0Oe1qzfx8l.png"></p><blockquote><div><p>It&rsquo;s so important to have correct grammar when talking - otherwise, like this cat, no one&rsquo;s going to be able to understand you!&nbsp;</p></div></blockquote><p>So first let&rsquo;s learn how&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2379;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>honaa</em> changes and then we&rsquo;ll see a bunch examples - does that sound like a good idea? Here we&rsquo;ll use what we learnt from&nbsp;<a href="../853847321/lesson-15-pronouns">Lesson #15 Pronouns</a>, if you can&rsquo;t remember that lesson then go back to it and revise over it!&nbsp;So are you ready to get going? Deep breath!&nbsp;</p><p><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em>main hoon </em>&nbsp;- &nbsp;I am</p><p><big><big>&#2361;&#2350; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em>ham hain &nbsp; - &nbsp; </em>We&nbsp;are</p><p><big><big>&#2340;&#2370; &#2361;&#2376;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em>&nbsp;too hai &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp; </em>You are (Intimate)</p><p><big><big>&#2310;&#2346; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; </big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<em>aap hain &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp; </em>You are (Formal)</p><p><big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350; &#2361;&#2379;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em>tum ho &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; </em>You are (Casual)</p><p>(Remember we learnt in&nbsp;<a href="../853847321/lesson-15-pronouns">Lesson #15 Pronouns</a>&nbsp;that Hindi has three different word for 'you&rsquo; - so if you can&rsquo;t remember their difference head back to that lesson!)</p><p><big><big>&#2351;&#2361; &#2361;&#2376; </big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em>yeh hai &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;</em>He / She / This is &nbsp;(Near)</p><p><big><big>&#2351;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; </big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em>ye hain &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp;&nbsp;</em>These / They are &nbsp;(Near)</p><p><big><big>&#2357;&#2361; &#2361;&#2376; </big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em>voh hai &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;</em>He / She / That is (Far)</p><p><big><big>&#2357;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; </big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em>ve hain &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp; &nbsp;</em>Those / They are (Far)&nbsp;</p><p>Phew! How was there? There&rsquo;s a lot to remember don&rsquo;t you think? Well actually there&rsquo;s just three (and a bit) rules you really need to know -&nbsp;</p><ol><li><big><big>&#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>hoon</em> means 'am&rsquo;. So whenever you want to say 'I am&rsquo; you&rsquo;ll say <big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>main hoon</em>.</li><li><big><big>&#2361;&#2376;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>hai</em> means 'is&rsquo;. So whenever you want to say 'is&rsquo; you&rsquo;ll say <big><big>&#2361;&#2376;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>hai</em></li><li><big><big>&#2361;&#2376;&#2306;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>hain</em> means 'are&rsquo;. So whenever you want to say 'are&rsquo; you&rsquo;ll say <big><big>&#2361;&#2376;&#2306;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>hain</em>.</li></ol><p>There&rsquo;s two exceptions to this though; We use <big><big>&#2361;&#2379;</big></big> <em>ho</em> for <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big> <em>tum</em> and we use&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2376;</big></big> <em>hai</em> for <big><big>&#2340;&#2370; </big></big><em>too</em>. It can be tricky to remember I know so keep practicing and you&rsquo;ll get there! &nbsp;</p><p>Now do you think you&rsquo;re ready for a few examples? Before we start there&rsquo;s one thing you need to know - in Hindi the always verb comes at the end of the sentence! This means we literally say &ldquo;I Nita am&rdquo; or &ldquo;this house is&rdquo;. This can be super confusing to new learners so be sure to go through the examples slowly!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mdotswyfxN1qzfx8l.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2344;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; </big></big><em>main neetaa hoon&nbsp;</em>- I am Nita&nbsp;</p><p>Can you see what&rsquo;s happened here? If you don&rsquo;t know, <big><big>&#2344;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366;</big></big> <em>nitaa</em> is a common girls name in india. Remember we are literally saying &ldquo;I Nita am&rdquo;. Ready for another example?</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mdoua9GlEL1qzfx8l.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2357;&#2375; &#2325;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366;&#2348;&#2375;&#2306; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ve kitaaben hain&nbsp;</em>- They are books</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mdotxy1LNO1qzfx8l.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big> &#2351;&#2361; &#2348;&#2367;&#2354;&#2381;&#2354;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376;&nbsp;</big></big><em>yeh billee hai&nbsp;</em>- This is [a/the] cat</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_mdoudnq2ja1qzfx8l.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;? </big></big><em>aap kaise hain? - </em>How are you?</p><p>We&rsquo;ve learnt this phrase, &ldquo;how are you?&rdquo;, and how to reply to it, already in&nbsp;<a href="../862964443/lesson-17-how-are-you">Lesson #17</a>&nbsp;- so feel free to check it out!&nbsp;</p><p>Phew ok! How&rsquo;s that? Can you follow the examples? There might be some words you don&rsquo;t understand in the sentences but don&rsquo;t worry, just make sure you can spot the&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2379;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>honaa&nbsp;</em>and how and why it&rsquo;s changed in each sentence! Try writing your own sentences and leave them as a comment below for practice!&nbsp;</p><p><a href="../../beginner">Back to Beginner&rsquo;s Grammar</a></p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/aug2010">aug2010</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/verbs">verbs</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="899032290" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_899032290"><iframe id="like_iframe_899032290" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=899032290&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=20ymarQv" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_899032290"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/899032290/20ymarQv" class="reblog_button"style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;"><svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" fill="#ccc"><path d="M5.01092527,5.99908429 L16.0088498,5.99908429 L16.136,9.508 L20.836,4.752 L16.136,0.083 L16.1360004,3.01110845 L2.09985349,3.01110845 C1.50585349,3.01110845 0.9792